  \section{Introduction}
  \label{sec:intro-paperC}
  Access control in multi-stakeholder environments faces a fundamental tension; devices and services must continue operating when disconnected from central infrastructure, yet security-critical decisions---especially credential revocation---must eventually be enforced consistently across all parties. This tension is particularly acute in industrial IoT\cite{MISTRY2020106382,liu2020fabriciot}, healthcare\cite{HASSELGREN2020104040}, and cross-organizational data sharing\cite{10.1145/3511899,DU2024101878}, where equipment changes hands between manufacturers, operators, and service providers throughout its lifecycle.

  A factory operates hundreds of programmable controllers on a restricted network. Maintenance is performed by engineers from different vendors who are granted temporary access to specific machines. Controllers may run for days without reliable connectivity\cite{9551736,s23208535}. An engineer can update a safety parameter while offline using a credential issued by their employer; hours later, that credential may be revoked after a safety incident. When logs from different controllers are later synchronized, the system must deterministically agree on which parameter changes were authorized and produce an audit trail showing who changed what, under which permission, and when.

   A consortium of universities shares sensitive research datasets for multi-site studies. Each institution retains authority over which researchers can access which datasets, and these permissions change as projects evolve and personnel move between institutions. Researchers work on datasets locally, sometimes offline on laptops during fieldwork or travel, and later synchronize. When a researcher's affiliation changes or a project ends, their access must be revoked. The system must converge to a consistent view of which analyses were authorized and produce an auditable record for compliance reporting.

   During disaster response, firefighters, medical teams, and external contractors share access to digital maps and sensor data on tablets that frequently lose connectivity. Permissions change as roles change during the operation. Devices must remain functional offline, but once connectivity is restored, all parties must converge on which actions were permitted and retain a tamper-evident record for later review.

  Across these settings, systems increasingly operate without continuous connectivity or centralized control---due to infrastructure failures, extreme operating environments, organizational boundaries, or deliberate air-gapping. This makes authorization in this context, an \emph{offline-first} problem; nodes must decide locally, yet the overall system must later reconcile those decisions into a consistent and auditable authorization state.

This results in the following problem statement. 

How can multiple independent authorities issue and revoke fine-grained permissions for shared resources that operate offline for extended periods, while ensuring that all parties eventually converge on the same authorized state and can verify a tamper-evident history of access decisions?

We call the model \ecac{} (Eventually Consistent Access Control). Our Rust prototype implementation is \equack{} (repository: \texttt{equack-core}), which we use for all experiments.

 This paper makes the following contributions:
  \begin{enumerate}
      \item \textit{Problem analysis and requirements derivation} (Section~\ref{sec:problem-analysis-paperC}): A systematic analysis of the offline multi-stakeholder authorization problem, identifying why existing paradigms (centralized IAM, token-based schemes, CRDTs, blockchains) fail to meet the required combination of properties, and deriving requirements from the motivating use cases. A mechanism-level comparison across five axes (ordering, revocation, trust distribution, audit, availability) is provided in Section~\ref{sec:mech-compare}.
      
      \item \textit{\ecac{} model and formal guarantees} (Section~\ref{sec:model-paperC}): An eventually consistent access control model that treats authorization evidence (issuer keys, status lists, grants, revokes) as first-class replicated state, enabling offline verification without a central PDP. We provide formal guarantees for determinism, convergence, policy safety, and audit integrity.
      
      \item \textit{Deterministic deny-wins replay semantics} (Section~\ref{sec:model-paperC}): A mechanism combining causal DAG ordering with deny-wins policy enforcement that ensures revoked credentials have no effect on post-reconciliation state---even if revocation arrives after the operations it invalidates.
      
      \item \textit{Implementation and evaluation} (Sections~\ref{sec:impl-paperC}--\ref{sec:eval-paperC}): The \equack{} prototype, a Rust implementation demonstrating practical performance (45k ops/s throughput, 8--11$\times$ checkpoint speedup) and empirical validation of the formal guarantees across randomized delivery orderings, partition-merge scenarios, and multi-issuer conflicts.
  \end{enumerate}

