\section{Problem Analysis}\label{sec:problem-analysis-paperC}

The offline multi-stakeholder authorization problem arises when systems must (i) continue operating during network partitions, (ii) support multiple independent authorities that can grant and revoke permissions, and (iii) eventually converge to a consistent, auditable authorization state. This section defines the problem context, presents conceptual requirements derived from motivating use cases, and evaluates existing approaches against those requirements.

%\subsection{System and Threat Context}\label{subsec:context-paperC}

Before defining requirements or comparing paradigms, we state the assumptions that shape our problem space. Section~\ref{subsec:systemModel} formalizes the full system and threat model; here we state only the assumptions needed to interpret R1--R6 and the subsequent comparisons.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Offline-first operation.} Replicas may be disconnected for extended periods (hours to days). Solutions requiring continuous connectivity to a central PDP or global consensus are excluded by construction.
    \item \textbf{Multi-authority governance.} Multiple independent organizations issue and revoke credentials. No single root authority controls all permissions.
    \item \textbf{Eventual delivery.} All well-formed operations are eventually delivered to all correct replicas, though delivery order is arbitrary and may be adversarially influenced.
    \item \textbf{Adversary capabilities.} An adversary may delay, reorder, or partition messages; compromise subject credentials; and attempt to tamper with local logs. The adversary is computationally bounded.
    \item \textbf{Out of scope.} We do not solve full Byzantine governance (colluding majorities of issuers) or physical key compromise. These require additional mechanisms.
\end{itemize}

This context explains why common fixes fail: online introspection endpoints violate offline-first; global consensus violates availability during partition; single-authority trust violates multi-stakeholder governance.

\subsection{The Offline Enforcement Problem}

Consider a set of replicas $R = \{r_1, \ldots, r_n\}$ operated by multiple stakeholders, maintaining shared resources under access control. Each replica may be offline for extended periods, during which it must make local authorization decisions. When replicas reconnect, they must reconcile their local states into a globally consistent outcome.

The core difficulty is not issuing permissions---standard PKI and token mechanisms suffice for that---but ensuring that all replicas eventually agree on \emph{which operations were authorized at the time they occurred}, despite:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Partition-time divergence}: Different replicas may observe different subsets of grants, revokes, and data operations during a partition.
    \item \textbf{Out-of-order delivery}: A revocation may arrive at a replica after operations it should have invalidated.
    \item \textbf{Multi-authority conflicts}: Independent issuers may make conflicting decisions (e.g., one grants while another revokes) that must be resolved deterministically.
\end{itemize}

Jacob and Hartenstein~\cite{jacob2024eventuallyac} formalize this limitation, showing that traditional access control models cannot provide meaningful guarantees under partition without additional mechanisms.

\subsection{System Model}\label{subsec:systemModel}

We consider a set of replicas operated by multiple stakeholders (organizations) that jointly maintain a replicated log of operations over shared resources. Replicas are deployed in environments with intermittent connectivity (e.g., edge and industrial deployments) and may be offline for extended periods. Each replica locally stores all received operations and materializes application state by deterministic replay.

%\paragraph{Principals and authorities.}
A \emph{subject} (principal) is an actor that initiates operations (users, services, devices). One or more independent \emph{issuers} create and revoke time-bounded credentials for subjects. Each replica hosts a policy enforcement point (PEP) that admits subject requests only when locally authorized. The PEP then emits a signed log event that carries the subject identity and authorization evidence (e.g., the VC). Importantly, the event timestamp (HLC) and the event signature are produced by the replica/PEP, not by the subject, preventing a compromised subject from forging or backdating log entries under our threat model.

%\paragraph{Operations and dissemination.}
All state changes---data updates, grants, revokes, and trust updates---are represented as signed operations in a causal DAG. Replicas disseminate operations using gossip/anti-entropy and fetch missing dependencies (parents) until replay can proceed. We assume an asynchronous network: messages can be delayed, reordered, duplicated, or temporarily dropped.

\subsection{Threat Model and Assumptions}

\ecac{} targets security failures that arise specifically from \emph{offline enforcement} and \emph{multi-authority governance}: stale credentials, conflicting grants and revokes across partitions, and post-hoc manipulation of authorization history.

We assume an adversary may (i) compromise subject credentials (e.g., steal a valid VC or authentication token) and attempt to request unauthorized operations, (ii) control the network to delay, reorder, or partition replicas, and (iii) attempt to tamper with stored history or audit records on one or more replicas. However, the adversary cannot forge replica/PEP signing keys or arbitrarily choose the HLC timestamps of accepted log events. The adversary is computationally bounded and cannot break standard cryptographic primitives.

The following assumptions scope the guarantees claimed by \ecac{}:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Honest-but-buggy administrators.} Issuers and policy administrators follow protocols but may make configuration errors; \ecac{} provides safety-by-default semantics that limit the effect of ambiguous concurrent decisions.
    \item \textbf{Eventual delivery.} Every well-formed operation is eventually delivered to every correct replica (e.g., via anti-entropy), although delivery order is arbitrary.
    \item \textbf{No physical compromise of key material.} Long-term private keys and tag keys are not exfiltrated via physical attacks on devices; compromise is modeled at the software/account level.
    \item \textbf{Bounded partition duration.} Offline periods are finite; after reconnection, replicas reconcile by exchanging missing operations.
\end{enumerate}

%\paragraph{Out of scope.}
\ecac{} does not attempt to provide safety against a fully Byzantine ecosystem in which all participants collude, nor does it address side-channel leakage or cryptographic primitive failures. Metadata privacy (hiding access patterns or policy structure) is treated as future work.

\subsection{Conceptual Requirements}\label{subsec:requirements-paperC}

From the system context and motivating use cases (Section~\ref{sec:intro-paperC}), we derive six conceptual requirements for offline multi-stakeholder access control. These serve as criteria for comparing existing paradigms and guiding ECAC's design. They are not exhaustive requirements-engineering outputs, but problem-derived design drivers.

%We distinguish between \emph{functional requirements} (what the system must guarantee) and \emph{non-functional requirements} (practical deployment constraints).

%\medskip
%\noindent\textbf{Functional Requirements:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{R1---Offline enforceability.} Authorization decisions must be enforceable without contacting a central PDP or ledger; disconnected nodes operate using locally verifiable evidence.
    
    \emph{Why it matters}: The industrial maintenance engineer must update controller parameters while the factory network is partitioned; the disaster responder must access sensor data on a tablet with no connectivity.
    
    \emph{What breaks without it}: Systems fail closed (blocking legitimate operations) or fail open (admitting unauthorized operations with stale cached policies).
    
    \item \textbf{R2---Deterministic post-partition convergence.} Given the same set of policy and credential events, all parties must compute the same final authorization state regardless of message arrival order.
    
    \emph{Why it matters}: After the factory's controllers reconnect, all must agree on which parameter changes were authorized. After university researchers synchronize, all institutions must see the same audit of which analyses were permitted.
    
    \emph{What breaks without it}: Non-deterministic outcomes create disputes, audit failures, and security violations where different replicas disagree on system state.
    
    \item \textbf{R3---Revocation safety under partition.} Revocations must deterministically invalidate effects in the replicated state after reconciliation, even if the revocation arrives after the operations it should have blocked. The vulnerability window during partition is bounded by partition duration.
    
    \emph{Why it matters}: When a maintenance engineer's credential is revoked after a safety incident, any parameter changes made after revocation must be invalidated upon log merge. When a researcher leaves a university, their post-departure analyses must be excluded from the reconciled state.
    
    \emph{What breaks without it}: Revoked principals retain effective access; post-reconciliation state includes unauthorized operations; audit trails are inconsistent with actual authorization.
    
    \emph{Important clarification}: Revocation invalidates effects in the replicated digital state, but cannot undo irreversible physical-world actions. Cyber-physical scenarios require compensating controls at the application layer.
    
    \item \textbf{R4---Tamper-evident accountability.} The history of grants, revokes, and authorization decisions must form an append-only, verifiable trace that cannot be altered or erased without detection.
    
    \emph{Why it matters}: Regulatory compliance requires demonstrable proof of who accessed what data and when. Post-incident forensics requires an unmodifiable record of authorization decisions.
    
    \emph{What breaks without it}: Malicious actors can alter history to cover tracks; compliance audits fail; disputes cannot be resolved by appeal to authoritative records.
\end{enumerate}

%\medskip
%\noindent\textbf{Non-Functional Requirements:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \setcounter{enumi}{4}
    \item \textbf{R5---Decentralized multi-authority issuance.} Independent issuers must be able to grant and revoke permissions without coordination; verifiers must check authenticity and status offline using locally available evidence.
    
    \emph{Why it matters}: In the federated university scenario, each institution must independently manage its researchers' access. In disaster response, multiple agencies issue credentials independently.
    
    \emph{What breaks without it}: Cross-organizational coordination bottlenecks; single points of failure; inability to operate across trust boundaries.
    
    \item \textbf{R6---Confidentiality with post-revocation protection.} Unauthorized parties should not read protected content. After revocation, a principal should not be able to decrypt data created after their access ended.
    
    \emph{Why it matters}: Research datasets contain sensitive information; industrial parameters may be proprietary. Leaver security (post-revocation confidentiality) ensures that after revocation-triggered key rotation, a revoked principal who does not obtain the new tag key cannot decrypt data created after their access ended.
    
    \emph{What breaks without it}: Data leakage to unauthorized parties; compromised credentials expose all past and future data; no meaningful confidentiality boundary.
\end{enumerate}

 We do not claim a general solution to Byzantine fault tolerance. While ECAC provides safety under honest-but-buggy administrators and can scope trust to individual issuers, it does not address scenarios where a quorum of issuers collude maliciously or where cryptographic key material is compromised through physical attacks.

