\subsubsection{Centralized IAM}

Centralized IAM systems (directory services, enterprise PDP/PEP architectures) provide a single, consistent policy view when connectivity to the decision point is reliable. Their design couples enforcement to online coordination---a partition or unreachable PDP either blocks access outright or forces fallbacks to cached decisions that become stale under revocation.~\cite{jacob2024eventuallyac,nasab2023empirical,7442163}

\textbf{Failure against R1, R3}: In the industrial maintenance scenario, if the PDP is unreachable, a maintenance engineer cannot update safety parameters---even with a valid credential. Alternatively, if cached permissions are used, a revoked engineer may continue operating after a safety incident.

\subsubsection{Token-Based Authorization}

Bearer tokens and certificates enable offline signature checks, partially addressing R1. The dominant weakness is revocation (R3): short-lived tokens trade availability for frequent renewal, while long-lived tokens create a vulnerability window that is difficult to bound without online checks (CRLs/OCSP), reintroducing connectivity dependence.~\cite{rouhani2021distributed,SINGH2022102503,s21206815,8386853}

\textbf{Failure against R2, R3}: In the federated university scenario, a researcher whose affiliation changed may continue accessing datasets until their token expires. Two replicas may reach different authorization conclusions if their local revocation information differs.

\subsubsection{Pure CRDT Replication}

CRDTs provide strong eventual consistency for replicated data types under concurrent updates~\cite{shapiro2011crdt,gomes2017_sec} (R1, R2 for data). However, CRDTs alone do not define authorization semantics: they merge state updates but do not answer whether an update \emph{should} apply under time-varying policy and revocation.

\textbf{Failure against R3, R4}: In the disaster response scenario, if a responder's role is revoked on one partition while they continue writing on another, a naive CRDT merge includes those writes---violating revocation semantics and producing an audit trail that does not reflect actual authorization.

\subsubsection{Blockchain and Ledger-Based Access Control}

Blockchains offer a globally ordered, immutable log (R2, R4) and distribute authority (R5). The trade-off is availability: producing the log requires consensus, incompatible with offline enforcement during partition.~\cite{8989788,9020182,9446108,8798730}

\textbf{Failure against R1}: In the industrial maintenance scenario, a controller cannot commit a safety-critical parameter update while disconnected. The operation must wait for reconnection and consensus---unacceptable for real-time operation.

\subsection{Summary and Design Direction}

Each paradigm can be extended with additional infrastructure, but these extensions typically reintroduce online dependencies or broaden trust assumptions. The gap analysis confirms that no existing approach simultaneously satisfies R1--R6.

This motivates ECAC's design: a log-based, offline-verifiable model with deterministic replay. By treating authorization evidence (issuer keys, status lists, grants, revokes) as first-class events in the same causal log as data, and enforcing a deny-wins gate during replay, ECAC aims to satisfy all six requirements without requiring online consensus or a central PDP. Section~\ref{sec:model-paperC} presents the model in detail.

