\subsection{Event Log and Deterministic Deny-Wins Replay}

\ecac{} maintains an append-only event log structured as a causal DAG, where each event points to its causal predecessors. The DAG encodes happens-before relations, and system state is derived by deterministically sorting and replaying events. A fixed traversal order ensures every replica produces the same sequence.

%\paragraph{Why deterministic ordering matters.}
The total ordering of events is central to \ecac{}'s guarantees. Without a deterministic order, replicas receiving the same events in different network orderings could reach different authorization outcomes---violating R2 and creating audit discrepancies. The ordering mechanism also enables dispute resolution across organizations: all parties can independently verify the same sequence of events and reach the same conclusions.

Concurrent events---those without causal order---are resolved using a composite timestamp: a Hybrid Logical Clock (HLC) value plus a unique operation ID. The HLC combines physical and logical time to preserve causality; when timestamps match, op IDs break ties deterministically. Replay thus becomes a pure function of the event set, guaranteeing identical state across replicas.

The replay-and-deny pipeline follows a clear separation of concerns: the DAG/topological order fixes a deterministic traversal, GRANT/REVOKE/TRUST events build auxiliary authorization state (epochs and TrustView), and only authorized DATA events are applied to the CRDT state; everything else is a deterministic, replayed prerequisite for the gate.

