Replay follows a deny-wins rule: apply if authorized at event time, else skip. Each event carries its logical timestamp and is applied only if the actor held the required permission at that moment. Unauthorized events become no-ops. This timestamp-ordered authorization ensures that policy-invalid actions have no effect on final state. The combination of causal order, deterministic tie-breaks, and deny-wins replay guarantees all replicas omit the same unauthorized operations, yielding a uniform, policy-consistent result (R2).

\paragraph{Dissemination and liveness.}
Operations are disseminated using secure gossip and anti-entropy synchronization (implemented with libp2p in our prototype). Replicas announce new operation identifiers and fetch missing operations (in particular missing parents) until the causal DAG is complete. This networking layer affects \emph{liveness}---how quickly replicas receive the same event set---but it does not affect the \emph{safety} and determinism claims: once a replica has received a set of well-formed operations, authorization and replay are purely local and deterministic.

\subsection{Authorization Epochs via Verifiable Credentials and Status Lists}

\ecac{} manages permissions using verifiable, time-bounded credentials. It adopts the W3C Verifiable Credentials (VC) format for signed authorization tokens asserting a principal's rights over a specific interval (validFrom--validUntil). Credentials are tamper-evident and self-verifying; replicas independently confirm authenticity and validity.

Revocations use standard VC status lists---cryptographically signed bitstrings indicating whether each credential ID is revoked. A valid credential defines an authorization epoch; expiry or revocation ends it.

Trust evidence is carried in-band as TRUST events (issuer keys and status-list updates) and is replayed into a local TrustView. GRANT/REVOKE events reference credentials and principals, while TrustView provides the key material and revocation snapshots needed to validate those credentials offline. Embedding this data removes dependence on a central authority: an offline node can verify at any timestamp that a user held a valid, non-revoked credential. The log itself forms a distributed PKI, replicating issuer keys and revocation data across nodes for local, offline validation. This is anchored by a pinned, cross-signed genesis checkpoint digest that bootstraps the initial issuer keys (and policy configuration) before any in-band trust updates are accepted.

During replay, the system checks for a valid credential covering each event's timestamp. If found, the operation applies; otherwise, it is skipped. These time-scoped credentials enforce temporal access control: users cannot act outside active grant intervals, and all replicas reach identical decisions since they verify identical evidence.

\ecac{}'s authorization model thus uses decentralized, verifiable credentials to issue and revoke rights securely, allowing any node to reconstruct \emph{who} was allowed to do \emph{what} and \emph{when}---without contacting any live identity service.

The in-band trust assembly and VC verification flow are illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:trustview-vc-paperC}. Trust operations (IssuerKey, IssuerKeyRevoke, StatusListChunk) build the TrustView incrementally during replay; when a VC must be checked, replicas parse the JWT, look up the issuer key in TrustView, verify the Ed25519 signature, check status-list revocation, and extract claims. This is the mechanism that makes offline verification credible: the key material and revocation evidence required to evaluate credentials is replicated as first-class log state rather than fetched from an online service.

