\subsection{Policy Semantics (Cedar) and Deny-Overrides Alignment}

\ecac{} builds on verifiable credentials with a rich policy layer inspired by AWS's Cedar language, an open-source ABAC framework. Policies may permit or forbid actions, with a default deny stance: if nothing explicitly permits, access is denied. \ecac{} adopts Cedar's deny-overrides (forbid-wins) semantics to extend the deny-wins rule across partitions.

If any matching policy forbids an operation, that denial overrides all permits. During replay, \ecac{} evaluates policies at the event's timestamp. If a forbid rule applies, the event is skipped; if only permits apply, it proceeds; if no rules apply, the default deny skips it. This mirrors XACML/Cedar's deny-overrides algorithm, ensuring predictable, safe-by-default access control.

\ecac{} unifies RBAC and ABAC: roles are attributes of principals (e.g., \texttt{role="admin"}), and policies can grant permissions directly or through roles. Cedar's entity-attribute model supports hierarchical roles and contextual attributes (department, clearance, object sensitivity, time-of-day), enabling fine-grained, context-aware rules alongside traditional role-based logic.

Policies reference system state---credentials and object metadata---and are evaluated deterministically. Identical inputs guarantee identical outcomes across replicas. The deny-overrides rule ensures partition-tolerant enforcement: a REVOKE event deterministically terminates any authorization epoch opened by a prior (or concurrent) GRANT in the replay order, so that earlier permits cannot ``win'' due to message reordering.

Importantly, ECAC does \emph{not} make revocation irreversible: a GRANT that appears \emph{after} a REVOKE in the replay order can open a fresh epoch (a re-grant) using new credential evidence. For concurrent GRANT/REVOKE pairs, the deterministic linearization chooses a single order: if $\textsc{Revoke}\,\triangleleft\,\textsc{Grant}$ then the GRANT is interpreted as a re-grant after revocation; if $\textsc{Grant}\,\triangleleft\,\textsc{Revoke}$ then the REVOKE closes the epoch opened by that grant.

Authorization epoch construction and the deny-wins gate are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:deny-wins-paperC}. Grant operations open epochs by recording subject, role, scope, and temporal bounds from the VC. Revoke operations close epochs by setting the end position. During replay, each DATA operation is evaluated at its event time: the gate checks epoch coverage, role permissions, scope intersection, and temporal validity before deterministically applying or skipping the operation.

