\subsection{Tamper-Evident Audit Trail}

\ecac{} treats auditing as a first-class design goal rather than an operational afterthought. During deterministic replay, each replica emits an \emph{audit record} for every operation that is eligible for enforcement (in particular DATA operations), indicating whether the operation was \emph{applied} or \emph{skipped} and why (missing authorization epoch, matching deny policy, invalid signature/status evidence). Audit records are linked in an append-only hash chain and signed, making any internal inconsistency (bit-flip, splice, reorder, or deletion) detectable \emph{relative to a pinned chain head digest} (e.g., a checkpoint hash recorded out-of-band or cross-signed by stakeholders).

A self-contained hash chain cannot prevent an attacker from presenting a valid prefix (truncation) unless the verifier has an external reference (a previously observed/pinned head digest) or can compare against another honest replica. Accordingly, we treat audit tamper-evidence as relative to such a reference.

Because replay order and authorization checks are deterministic functions of the same input event set, independent replicas that ingest the same operations compute the same apply/skip decisions and can therefore validate each other's audit traces after reconciliation. This supports R4 (tamper-evident accountability) without requiring a globally ordered online ledger.

\subsection{Confidentiality and Key Rotation}

\ecac{} supports an optional confidentiality layer based on per-tag payload encryption. Each DATA operation is associated with a tag $\tau$ and carries ciphertext $c := \mathsf{Enc}_{K_{\tau}^{(v)}}(m)$ together with the key version $v$. To preserve convergence, ciphertext (and its version metadata) is replicated and replayed like any other payload; replicas do not treat encrypted operations as no-ops.

Access control is enforced at \emph{query time}: a subject receives plaintext only if the deny-wins gate authorizes the corresponding read action for tag $\tau$ under the reconstructed authorization state. Unauthorized subjects receive a redacted view (e.g., ciphertext, hashes, or placeholders) while still being able to verify log integrity and reproduce the same deterministic state digest.

To limit exposure after membership changes, the system can rotate the tag key on revocation. A KeyRotate event advances $K_{\tau}^{(v)}$ to $K_{\tau}^{(v+1)}$, and subsequent writes use $v{+}1$. The new key is distributed in-band via KeyGrant records that encrypt $K_{\tau}^{(v+1)}$ to the public keys of subjects authorized to read tag $\tau$.

This provides \emph{leaver security} (often called forward secrecy in group key management): after a rotation point, a revoked subject that does not obtain $K_{\tau}^{(v+1)}$ cannot decrypt ciphertexts produced under version $v{+}1$. We do not claim backward secrecy for joiners unless the system also rotates keys on grant. \equack{}-core includes this path as an experimental component; accordingly, we treat confidentiality results as indicative and focus the evaluation on overhead rather than a full cryptographic validation.

The per-tag encryption and key rotation mechanisms are illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:confidentiality-paperC}. Data operations are encrypted using the tag's current symmetric key (XChaCha20-Poly1305). KeyRotate operations establish new key versions, and KeyGrant operations distribute keys encrypted to authorized subjects' public keys. The leaver security timeline highlights the intended security outcome: after a rotation triggered by revocation, principals lacking the new key can still verify and replicate the log but cannot decrypt newly produced ciphertexts for that tag.

