\paragraph{Code excerpt: Deny-wins gate.}
The following excerpt illustrates the deny-wins gate evaluation with \emph{position+time} epoch coverage, which is central to R3 (revocation safety):

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Rust]
fn evaluate_gate(
    event: &DataEvent,
    pos: u64,
    epochs: &EpochStore,
    policy: &Policy
) -> GateResult {
    let t_ms = event.hlc().physical_ms();
    let (subj, act, res) = event.authorization_tuple();

    // Check epoch coverage (position + time)
    let epoch_ok = epochs.covers(subj, act, pos, t_ms);
    if !epoch_ok {
        return GateResult::Skip(SkipReason::NoEpoch);
    }

    // Evaluate Cedar policy (deny-overrides)
    match policy.evaluate(subj, act, res, event.attrs()) {
        PolicyResult::Allow => GateResult::Apply,
        PolicyResult::Deny(reason) =>
            GateResult::Skip(SkipReason::PolicyDeny(reason)),
    }
}
\end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{Code excerpt: Deterministic linearization.}
The Kahn-based topological sort with \texttt{BTreeSet<(Hlc, OpId)>} tie-break that ensures deterministic ordering (R2):

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Rust]
fn linearize_dag(events: &[Event]) -> Vec<EventId> {
    // Build indegree + adjacency
    let (indeg, children) = build_graph(events);

    // Ready set: deterministic min-heap by (hlc, op_id)
    let mut ready = BTreeSet::<(Hlc, OpId, EventId)>::new();
    for e in events {
        if indeg[e.id()] == 0 {
            ready.insert((e.hlc(), e.op_id(), e.id()));
        }
    }

    let mut out = Vec::with_capacity(events.len());
    let mut indeg = indeg;

    while let Some(&min) = ready.iter().next() {
        ready.remove(&min);
        let (_, _, id) = min;
        out.push(id);
        for &child in &children[&id] {
            indeg[child] -= 1;
            if indeg[child] == 0 {
                let ce = lookup(child);
                ready.insert((ce.hlc(), ce.op_id(), child));
            }
        }
    }

    out
}
\end{lstlisting}


\section{Evaluation}
\label{sec:eval-paperC}

We evaluate \equack{} through deterministic experiments designed to (i) provide empirical evidence consistent with the formal guarantees and (ii) quantify replay performance. This section demonstrates the key behaviors that \equack{} provides and shows what those behaviors mean in practice for offline multi-stakeholder systems.

The evaluation is organized around five questions:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Convergence} (R2): Do replicas receiving operations in different orders converge to identical states?
    \item \textbf{Revocation safety} (R3): Are post-revocation operations excluded from final state, even when revocation arrives after the operations?
    \item \textbf{Tamper evidence} (R4): Is audit-chain tampering detected?
    \item \textbf{Multi-authority resolution} (R5): Are conflicts between independent issuers resolved deterministically?
    \item \textbf{Practical performance}: What are the costs of replay, checkpointing, and encryption?
\end{enumerate}

All experiments use fixed seeds and a deterministic environment (\texttt{TZ=UTC, SOURCE\_DATE\_EPOCH=1}). This evaluation assumes offline operation without reliance on continuous global consensus, as required by R1.

\subsection{Experimental Methodology}\label{subsec:methodology-paperC}

\subsubsection{Testbed Configuration}
Experiments ran on a single Linux x86\_64 workstation using Rust 1.85 in release mode with deterministic environment settings and fixed seeds. Multi-node convergence (E12) is evaluated via in-process deterministic simulation; partition behavior is additionally validated via offline log merges.
We compute state digests as $\mathrm{blake3}(\mathrm{DOMAIN}\,\|\,\mathrm{canon}(\textit{state}))$, where $\mathrm{canon}(\cdot)$ is a canonical serialization with stable map/field ordering (to avoid encoding drift across executions). In \equack{}, $\mathrm{canon}(\cdot)$ is implemented as a deterministic byte serialization with stable key ordering.

