\subsection{Convergence Under Random Ordering (E1)}

\textbf{What this demonstrates}: \equack{}'s deterministic ordering ensures that message arrival order does not affect the final authorization state---critical for R2 and for resolving disputes across organizations.

\textbf{Method.} Generate a 10,000-op log using the concurrent workload. Create 100 valid orderings by permuting while respecting causal dependencies. Replay each independently and compare state digests.

\textbf{Results.} All 100 orderings produced identical digests (\texttt{\small cbab89ee...b7f493b2}), i.e., 100\% convergence under reordering. Mean replay time was 615~ms with $\sigma=18$~ms.

