\subsection{Deny-Wins Revocation (E3)}

\textbf{What this demonstrates}: Revocations deterministically invalidate post-revocation operations---critical for R3 (revocation safety under partition).

\textbf{Method.} Issue credential granting user $U$ write access. $U$ performs 1,000 writes; revoke after the first 500 writes. Replay and verify the first 500 writes are applied and the remaining 500 writes are skipped.

\textbf{Results.} Deny-wins correctly enforced revocation:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Total: 1,004 ops (1,000 Data + 1 Credential + 1 Grant + 1 Revoke + 1 IssuerKey)
    \item Applied: 500 pre-revocation writes
    \item Skipped: 500 post-revocation writes
    \item Digest: \texttt{\small 8da8b49e...46633fbf}
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Implication}: When a maintenance engineer's credential is revoked after a safety incident, all parameter changes made after revocation are excluded from the reconciled state---even if those changes were committed locally before the revocation message arrived.


\subsection{Revocation Under Partition (E11)}

\textbf{What this demonstrates}: The key scenario for \ecac{}---access-rule enforcement across a network partition, followed by reconciliation that invalidates post-revocation operations.

\textbf{Method.} Generate two partition logs (A, B). In partition A, a user is granted access, performs writes, then is revoked. In partition B (which has not yet received the revocation), the same user continues writing. Merge the logs and replay.

\textbf{Results.}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Pre-revocation writes (both partitions): Applied (50 ops)
    \item Post-revocation writes from partition B: Skipped (10 ops)
    \item Merged digest: \texttt{\small 69fae61e...1a2986c1}
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Implication}: This is exactly the disaster response scenario: a responder's role is revoked on one partition while they continue working on another. Upon reconnection, the unauthorized work is excluded from the merged state, and all parties converge on the same authorized subset of operations.


\subsection{Multi-Authority Conflict Resolution (E4)}

\textbf{What this demonstrates}: Independent issuers making conflicting grants and revokes are resolved deterministically---critical for R5 (multi-authority issuance).

\textbf{Method.} Configure three issuers ($I_1$, $I_2$, $I_3$) with overlapping authority. $I_1$ and $I_2$ grant user $U$ ``editor'' role at $t_1$, $t_2$; $I_3$ revokes at $t_3 > t_2$; $U$ writes at $t_4 > t_3$. Inject into 10 replicas in random orders.

\textbf{Results.} All replicas converged:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Total: 128 ops (3 issuers)
    \item Writes during $[t_1, t_3)$: accepted
    \item Writes after $t_3$: rejected (skipped)
    \item Digest: \texttt{\small f2fbb024...1103c2b2}
    \item Convergence: 100\%
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Implication}: In the federated university scenario, when different institutions issue conflicting permissions, all parties reach the same authorization outcome. The deny-wins semantics ensure that any revocation takes precedence.


\subsection{Audit Integrity (E5)}

\textbf{What this demonstrates}: Tampering with the audit trail is detectable relative to a pinned head digest---critical for R4 (tamper-evident accountability).

\textbf{Method.} Generate an audited log and compute the chain head digest $\mathrm{ch}_N$ from the untampered run. Then apply three tamper modes: (1) flip a byte in one record's payload, (2) delete one record from the pinned prefix, and (3) swap two adjacent records in the pinned prefix. For each mode, verify the chain against $\mathrm{ch}_N$.

\textbf{Results.} Chain verification succeeded on the untampered log against $\mathrm{ch}_N$. All three tamper modes failed verification: (1) bit-flip caused signature mismatch, (2) deletion caused a sequence gap/prev-hash mismatch, (3) reorder caused prev-hash mismatch. Each failure was detected at the exact tampered record.

\textbf{Implication}: Regulatory compliance and forensic investigation can rely on the audit chain when paired with a pinned head digest (e.g., from cross-signed checkpoints or an external transparency log). Any attempt to modify historical authorization decisions within the pinned prefix is detectable.


