\subsection{Limitations and Threats to Validity}\label{subsec:limitations-paperC}

\subsubsection{Inherent Limitations}

\noindent\textbf{No immediate revocation for offline nodes.} Disconnected nodes cannot learn of revocations until sync. Operations from revoked users are invalidated upon reconnection, but the vulnerability window equals partition duration.

\noindent\textbf{Append-only storage.} The log grows monotonically. Checkpointing reduces replay cost, but the full log must be retained for auditability.

\noindent\textbf{Replay cost after long partitions.} Long-offline nodes must replay large operation sets. Checkpoints mitigate but do not eliminate this.

\noindent\textbf{Metadata visibility.} Per-tag encryption protects payloads, but operation structure, timestamps, and producer keys remain visible. Full metadata privacy requires additional cryptographic machinery.

\noindent\textbf{Physical-world actions.} Revocation invalidates effects in the replicated digital state but cannot undo irreversible physical-world actions (e.g., a controller that has already actuated). Applications requiring staged commit or compensating controls must implement these at the application layer.

\subsubsection{Threats to Validity}

\noindent\textbf{Measurement density.} E6 replay scaling covers six log sizes with five trials each. E8 and E9 use fewer sizes; additional workload diversity (multi-key, concurrent writers) is needed to fully characterize scaling behavior.

\noindent\textbf{Single-machine setting.} Performance results are from one Linux x86\_64 workstation. E12 sync convergence uses in-process simulation rather than real network transport; actual network latency and packet loss would affect convergence timing.

\noindent\textbf{Workload representativeness.} Workloads are synthetic. Real deployments may involve different mixes. Validation on real traces remains future work.

\noindent\textbf{Cross-platform coverage.} E2 determinism is verified via a hardcoded digest on Linux x86\_64. Full cross-platform validation (aarch64, macOS, Windows) awaits CI infrastructure.


\section{Other Related Work}\label{sec:related-work-paperC}

\ecac{} is motivated by deployments where authorization must remain enforceable under intermittent connectivity and multi-organizational governance. Prior work spans (i) offline and edge access control, (ii) revocation and token-based authorization, (iii) eventual consistency mechanisms for replicated state, and (iv) ledger-based approaches for auditability and distributed trust.

\subsection{Offline and Edge Access Control}

Industrial IoT and edge platforms routinely face partitions and intermittent connectivity, motivating authorization mechanisms that remain available without a centralized policy decision point. Real deployments in industrial and healthcare domains highlight the practical constraints of fielded devices, including lifecycle transitions across stakeholders and the need for resilient local enforcement. \cite{MISTRY2020106382,liu2020fabriciot,HASSELGREN2020104040,9551736,s23208535}

\subsection{Token-Based Authorization and Revocation}

Bearer tokens, certificates, and capability-like schemes enable offline signature checks, but revocation remains a recurring limitation. Techniques such as short-lived tokens, revocation lists, and online status checks trade off availability against timeliness and introduce windows of residual access during partitions. \cite{rouhani2021distributed,SINGH2022102503,s21206815,8386853,zhang2020attribute}

\subsection{Eventual Consistency and CRDT-Based Replication}

CRDTs provide strong eventual consistency for replicated data types under concurrent updates~\cite{shapiro2011crdt,gomes2017_sec}, which aligns with the offline availability requirements of edge systems. However, CRDT abstractions typically address \emph{data convergence} rather than \emph{authorization convergence}: they do not define how access-control decisions should be incorporated into the merge semantics, nor how revocation should deterministically invalidate effects. Extensions for confidentiality under replication (e.g., merge-compatible encryption and leaver security) further increase complexity.

\subsection{Ledger-Based Audit and Decentralized Trust}

Blockchains and related replicated ledgers provide global ordering and tamper-evident history, making them attractive for distributed access control and accountability. Their use for edge enforcement is constrained by the need to reach consensus to finalize policy changes, and by the confidentiality and scalability concerns of storing policies and access metadata in a shared ledger. \cite{9020182,9446108,8798730,8989788,9548956,s20010282,s22031271}

\subsection{Positioning of \ecac{}}

\ecac{} complements these lines of work by (i) keeping enforcement offline-first and consensus-free, (ii) treating policy, revocation, and trust updates as first-class events in the same causal log as data, and (iii) enforcing a deterministic deny-wins replay semantics that guarantees convergence and policy safety after reconciliation. In contrast to token-based designs, \ecac{}'s authorization outcome is a deterministic function of the reconciled log; in contrast to ledger-based approaches, \ecac{} does not require online consensus to make progress during partition.

